  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Character is a person, being, or entity in a narrative whose actions, speech, thoughts, and relationships carry the story\u0026rsquo;s meaning. Characterization is the set of techniques a writer uses to make a character knowable to the reader.\nE.M. Forster distinguished between flat and round characters. Flat characters embody a single quality or idea and can be summarized in a sentence — they are not lesser for this, but they serve a different function than round characters, who surprise convincingly, whose behavior is complex enough that the reader can\u0026rsquo;t fully predict them [@forster1927]. The distinction is functional, not evaluative: a story needs both.\n",
